Looking at this problem, I need to prove that `Fintype.card (U k) = Fintype.card (T k)`.

The key insight is that the linear involution `linearInvo` maps between `T k` and `U k` in a way that establishes a bijection. Specifically, if we look at the involution `(x, y, z) ↦ (y, x, -z)`:
- Elements in `T k` have `z > 0`
- Elements in `U k` have `x - y + z > 0`

The involution swaps these conditions in a specific way. When applied to an element with `z > 0`, we get an element with `-z < 0`, and the condition `x - y + z > 0` becomes relevant for the image.

Let me construct a bijection between `T k` and `U k` using the linear involution.

```lean
theorem sameCard : Fintype.card (U k) = Fintype.card (T k) := by
  refine Fintype.card_eq.mpr ⟨?_⟩
  refine {
    toFun := fun ⟨⟨⟨x, y, z⟩, h⟩, hu⟩ => ⟨⟨⟨y, x, -z⟩, by
      simp only [S, Set.mem_setOf_eq] at h ⊢
      exact ⟨by linarith [h], h.2.2, h.2.1⟩⟩, by
      simp only [T, Set.mem_setOf_eq, U, Set.mem_setOf_eq] at hu ⊢
      linarith⟩
    invFun := fun ⟨⟨⟨x, y, z⟩, h⟩, ht⟩ => ⟨⟨⟨y, x, -z⟩, by
      simp only [S, Set.mem_setOf_eq] at h ⊢
      exact ⟨by linarith [h], h.2.2, h.2.1⟩⟩, by
      simp only [T, Set.mem_setOf_eq, U, Set.mem_setOf_eq] at ht ⊢
      linarith⟩
    left_inv := fun ⟨⟨⟨x, y, z⟩, h⟩, hu⟩ => by simp
    right_inv := fun ⟨⟨⟨x, y, z⟩, h⟩, ht⟩ => by simp
  }
